WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Our reading today comes from the 14th Psalm. It's also in the handout.

2
00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:19.000
The fool says in his heart, there is no God. They are corrupt. They do abominable deeds. There is none who does good.

3
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:28.000
The Lord looks down from heaven on the children of men to see if there are any who understand, who seek after God.

4
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:35.000
They have all turned aside. Together they have become corrupt. There is none who does good, not even one.

5
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Have they no knowledge? All the evil doers who eat up my people as they eat bread and do not call upon the Lord?

6
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:49.000
There they are in great terror, for God is with the generation of the righteous.

7
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:58.000
You would shame the plans of the poor, but the Lord is his refuge. Oh, that salvation for Israel would come out of Zion.

8
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
And the Lord restores the fortunes of his people. Let Jacob rejoice. Let Israel be glad.

9
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:06.000
The word of the Lord.

10
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Thanks be to God.

11
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Let's pray together.

12
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Lord, yes, you are sufficient and your word is sufficient as well.

13
00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:32.000
So Lord, I pray that as we come to your word now that you would supply what we need both for today, but also for eternity.

14
00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.000
In Jesus' name we pray. Amen.

15
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
I wonder what comes to mind when you think of a fool.

16
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
And you should not be looking at one another at the moment.

17
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Maybe think about a silly TV personality like Michael Scott from The Office or I don't know, Mr. Bean, something like that.

18
00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:02.000
There are certainly kind of real life examples when you think of, I know you hear about celebrities, rock stars, that kind of thing,

19
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
who really hit it big and live it up while the money lasts and then they lose everything.

20
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:17.000
I read not too long ago about a well-known singer and musician from the 70s who was then living in a van in California.

21
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:26.000
He was homeless, so went from having everything to having very little because of the foolish way he had chosen to live.

22
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Well, we can't be sure what would come to David's mind when it comes to a foolish person,

23
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.000
but we can have a pretty good idea of the sort of person he would have thought about,

24
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
particularly when it came to who he encountered in 1 Samuel 25.

25
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
There was a man called Nabal and there's no connection in this psalm,

26
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
you know how some of the psalms have a specific connection to a specific account.

27
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.000
We don't have that here.

28
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Nonetheless, you can't help but wonder if this guy came to mind.

29
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:01.000
This was back when David had been anointed as king, but he was still on the run from King Saul.

30
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:09.000
He and his men had made their way through an area where Nabal had a bunch of land where his sheep were there.

31
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Nabal was a very wealthy man and were told that he had thousands of sheep and goats

32
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
and he had lots of shepherds that worked under him to look after those sheep and those goats.

33
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.000
It was a feast day and you can read about the kind of ample supplies that he had.

34
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.000
He was able to really live it up.

35
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:30.000
This is a guy who seemed to have everything.

36
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:35.000
David thought, well, we've treated their shepherds really well.

37
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
It's a feast day when people would normally have their neighbors around

38
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
and would kind of celebrate together and share in their food and celebration.

39
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Surely on a day like today, they will help us out and supply a bit of what we need.

40
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.000
David sent a few of his men to go and speak to Nabal.

41
00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.000
Nabal's response was not a good response.

42
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Nabal basically said, David who? Who does he think he is?

43
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
He insulted David's men.

44
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:13.000
He said that he wasn't going to give them a thing and kind of sent them away empty-handed.

45
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:20.000
When word got back to David, David was furious and he would later say that his response wasn't the best.

46
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
He basically said, all right, I just sent a few last time.

47
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:25.000
Now I'm going to gather an entire army, which he did.

48
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
He gathered the whole army and he was basically going to come and wipe Nabal out.

49
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:38.000
He and the army were on the way, but Abigail, Nabal's wife, found out about what Nabal had done.

50
00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.000
She was mortified by her husband's behavior.

51
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Now some of you wives can identify with Abigail here.

52
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:50.000
So she said, I can't believe he said that and she heard that David and his army were on the way.

53
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
So she made her way out with a bunch of supplies, the kind of supplies they needed.

54
00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:01.000
The supplies got there first, so this gift came from Nabal's abundance because of Abigail giving it.

55
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And then Abigail came and she just apologized profusely.

56
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And she said she was so sorry for what had happened.

57
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:15.000
And then she said, you know, my husband, Nabal, has lived up to his name because his name means fool.

58
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:16.000
That's what his name meant.

59
00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
So my husband is living up to his name.

60
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.000
He is a fool.

61
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:22.000
So David actually accepts the apology.

62
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
He owns up to the fact that he was taking vengeance in his own hands.

63
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
So he was glad that she stopped him that day because it wasn't the right thing.

64
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
He should have left that to the Lord.

65
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
But when she came back to Nabal, he was none the wiser.

66
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
He was this guy who wouldn't welcome the king was at home feasting like a king.

67
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Like he was enjoying all his resources on this feast day and he was drunk as well.

68
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And he was just wasted.

69
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And so she came to him and she thought, well now's not the time to speak to him.

70
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.000
I'm going to speak to him in the morning.

71
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
So when the morning came and he'd sobered up, she came to him and told him what had happened.

72
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
That David and his army had almost wiped everybody out.

73
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:05.000
And we're told what happened to him.

74
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:08.000
He says that his heart seized up within him.

75
00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:11.000
And he died 10 days later.

76
00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.000
It says the Lord struck Nabal and he died.

77
00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:21.000
This is a cautionary, vivid tale that is before us in the Old Testament.

78
00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:26.000
So King Nabal, so to speak, defied the Lord anointed.

79
00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
And he decided to rule over his own little kingdom.

80
00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:34.000
But his power and the pleasures that came from it were enjoyable for a short time.

81
00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
But they were short lived.

82
00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:38.000
He'd made a short-sighted decision.

83
00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
He seemed to have it all.

84
00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:43.000
But in the end, Nabal lived up to his name.

85
00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
He proved to be a fool.

86
00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:50.000
So years later, David sits down and he writes a Psalm.

87
00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:55.000
And the first word he writes in Psalm 14 is Nabal.

88
00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
That's the word here when it says the fool says in his heart.

89
00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
The first word is Nabal says in his heart.

90
00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:08.000
So Nabal, in 1 Samuel 25, was not the first fool nor was he the last.

91
00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:17.000
So as we look at the Psalm, we would all do well to ask whether or not any of these Nabal-like characteristics are true of us.

92
00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
Well, this is our last Psalm we're going to be looking at in this kind of introduction to the book of Psalms.

93
00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.000
And this series we've been going through in the summer.

94
00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Well, we started in Psalm 1 and we saw there before us the way of the ungodly and the way of the righteous.

95
00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:39.000
And here we're kind of returning to that in some ways, but instead of it's talking about it as the way of the righteous and the way of the ungodly,

96
00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
it talks about the way of the righteous and the way of the fool.

97
00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:46.000
So the fool is the one who's in the place of the ungodly here, the ungodly fool.

98
00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.000
So we're just going to look at that together.

99
00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:54.000
So we'll look at the way of the fool and the three characteristics there and then the generation of the righteous or the way of the righteous.

100
00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.000
And we'll look at three characteristics there too.

101
00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:59.000
So first of all, the way of the fool.

102
00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:04.000
To just return back to Psalm 1, you might remember it's about the blessed man.

103
00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
Blessed is the man. That's where the book of Psalms begin.

104
00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And you have this blessed individual who's the personification really of a life that is truly blessed.

105
00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:21.000
And it points us to Jesus and the eternal spiritual blessings that we can know in him as the blessed man.

106
00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
Well Psalm 14 kind of begins in the opposite way.

107
00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Instead of it beginning blessed is the man, it begins the fool.

108
00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:36.000
So a foolish individual is put before us as the kind of personification of the kind of life we want to turn away from.

109
00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
It's the opposite of a life of blessing.

110
00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
So what are these three things that it tells us about the fool?

111
00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Well the first thing is that the fool is atheistic.

112
00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
The fool is atheistic. So let's read it.

113
00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:55.000
The fool says in his heart, there is no God.

114
00:08:55.000 --> 00:09:01.000
So that doesn't mean that someone who would say they're an atheist is not an intelligent person.

115
00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:07.000
Nevertheless, knowledge and wisdom are not the same thing.

116
00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:14.000
You can be an academic, you can be a best-selling author and still be a fool.

117
00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:19.000
But what's being addressed here isn't so much what we might call intellectual atheism.

118
00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.000
It's certainly included in that when the fool says there is no God,

119
00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
but it's not just intellectual atheism that's addressing here.

120
00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:30.000
It's what we might call practical atheism.

121
00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:39.000
So whether or not the fool believes that God exists theoretically, they live as though God did not exist.

122
00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
That's the point of what's being said here.

123
00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
So a few things that might lead us to that conclusion that that's what's being addressed here.

124
00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
I mean one, notice where the fool says there is no God.

125
00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:53.000
The fool says in his heart there is no God.

126
00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:57.000
So in Hebrew thought, the heart includes the intellect, certainly,

127
00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:02.000
but it also includes the emotions.

128
00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
It includes the will.

129
00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.000
So this is the whole person here.

130
00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:15.000
This is a decisive rejection of God coming from our mind, our will, our emotions.

131
00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
So it's not just somebody contemplating, do I think there's a God or not?

132
00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:22.000
It's somebody saying, I'm rejecting God.

133
00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:26.000
Another reason why we see this is more like practical atheism here is because

134
00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:32.000
actually the words there is, when it says there is no God, are not there in the original Hebrew.

135
00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.000
What it literally says is the fool says in his heart, no God.

136
00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:42.000
Now it's a perfectly fine translation and it does mean there is no God.

137
00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:47.000
But removing those two words can give us some insight into the sense of what's being said here.

138
00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:50.000
So the fool says in his heart, no God.

139
00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.000
It's like a sign on the door, like a no entry sign.

140
00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.000
It's like Nabal saying, David, David who?

141
00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.000
He is not welcome here.

142
00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Entry is denied.

143
00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:07.000
So the fool refuses to give God his rightful place in their heart.

144
00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:10.000
They say, no God for me.

145
00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
Thank you very much.

146
00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:18.000
It's like in Romans 1 where the apostle Paul talks about how in nature alone

147
00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:23.000
there is enough evidence to point us to the reality of God's existence.

148
00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:30.000
Nevertheless, people resist him, not merely on intellectual grounds, but on moral grounds.

149
00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:36.000
He says in Romans 1.18 how people suppress the truth in unrighteousness.

150
00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
Because what is to be known about God is plain.

151
00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
God's shown it to them.

152
00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:47.000
And he goes on to say, how those who claim to be wise become fools

153
00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:52.000
when they suppress the truth of the knowledge of God, that inner compass that points to God when they suppress that.

154
00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
They become fools.

155
00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:05.000
The author and agnostic Aldous Huxley once spoke very honestly about his mixed motivations for his unbelief.

156
00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:13.000
He made it clear it wasn't just purely on intellectual grounds that he didn't believe in God from a place of certainty.

157
00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
Let me read you a quote.

158
00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:18.000
It's kind of a long quote, but it's interesting to hear what he says.

159
00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:23.000
He said, I had motives for not wanting the world to have a meaning

160
00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:32.000
and consequently assumed that it had none and was able without any difficulty to find satisfying reasons for this assumption.

161
00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:39.000
The philosopher who finds no meaning in the world is not concerned exclusively with a problem in pure metaphysics.

162
00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:47.000
He is also concerned to prove that there is no valid reason why he personally should not do as he wants to do.

163
00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:59.000
For myself, as no doubt for most of my friends, the philosophy of meaninglessness was essentially an instrument of liberation from a certain system of morality.

164
00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:05.000
We objected to the morality because it interfered with our sexual freedom.

165
00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
So did you catch that?

166
00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:16.000
He didn't want to live under the constraints of the kind of morality that would come if God existed, if Scripture were true.

167
00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:28.000
And so because he didn't want to live under those constraints, he then looked for reasons that matched up with where he was already at in terms of his worldview and what he desired in life.

168
00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:34.000
So whether or not you believe in the existence of God, this kind of practical atheism here,

169
00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:41.000
following after what our hearts want and then adjusting our theology accordingly, is something that we can all be guilty of.

170
00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:46.000
In fact, every time we sin, we are living as practical atheists.

171
00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.000
We're living as though God didn't exist.

172
00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:57.000
Or whether or not we didn't want God to be in that particular area of our life.

173
00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:05.000
So the question we need to ask ourselves as we see this is, is the God who reigns over all welcome in my life?

174
00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Is he welcome in every area of my life?

175
00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:13.000
Or do I deny him access?

176
00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.000
And then this inward kind of posture of defiance against God.

177
00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:22.000
Like I don't want God in my life or I don't want God in this area of my life.

178
00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
That posture of defiance has lived out in practice.

179
00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:31.000
So it talks about how the fool says no God, but it also speaks repeatedly about no good, no good.

180
00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
So no God leads to no good.

181
00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:39.000
And there's a word that's used to describe this and it is corruption.

182
00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:48.000
So twice it speaks about the corruption of our state and our deeds that flow from that.

183
00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:53.000
So verse one again, but the second half says they are corrupt.

184
00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
They do abominable deeds. There is none who does good.

185
00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Go to verse three.

186
00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:03.000
They have all turned to sides. Together they have become corrupt.

187
00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.000
There was none who does good, not even one.

188
00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
So the fool is not only atheistic, but also corrupt.

189
00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:17.000
The word corrupt means spoiled, rotten, ruined.

190
00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.000
So maybe you've been in a situation where you go and you go to the fridge, get some milk out,

191
00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:27.000
and you pour that glass of milk and you take a big swig of it only to discover that it's soured.

192
00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:32.000
You know, just get this repulsive taste in your mouth. You've got to spit it out.

193
00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:35.000
I've certainly been in that position before. It's an awful feeling.

194
00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:38.000
And this is what it's saying about the fool.

195
00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
So the way of the fool is like that. It is off.

196
00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:44.000
And it can be seen in what they do.

197
00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.000
You see that kind of sourness there, but also in what they fail to do.

198
00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:52.000
It all comes back to this corruption.

199
00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:57.000
It's like what Paul says in Romans 8.

200
00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
He speaks about our flesh as being that corrupt part of us.

201
00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:04.000
And he says, those who are in the flesh cannot please God.

202
00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:08.000
In other words, this corruption has moved into every part of life.

203
00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
So we might...

204
00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
Let's move over to this for a second.

205
00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
We might see where it says there's none who does good and say,

206
00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
well, sure, I can think of good that's done by awful people.

207
00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
Like even the worst of us do good.

208
00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
And maybe just think about the sour milk for a second.

209
00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
So it would be technically true to say,

210
00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:30.000
well, there's parts of that sour milk, if you break down it to its various components,

211
00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
that are still good, you know.

212
00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
But are you going to drink that glass or not?

213
00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
No, because the sourness has affected the whole.

214
00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:41.000
There's a corruption that has affected the whole of it.

215
00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:45.000
So this is what Scripture says about our state apart from Christ.

216
00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
We are corrupt.

217
00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
The corruption has affected the whole.

218
00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:52.000
This is why in Isaiah, I think it's 64,

219
00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:57.000
speaks about our righteousness as being as filthy rags.

220
00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:01.000
This is our righteousness apart from the grace of God in Christ.

221
00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
There's a corruption that spills into everything.

222
00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And so our corrupt actions are coming from a heart of corruption.

223
00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:16.000
So this is not to, I mean, there's an element of the idea of,

224
00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
say, pushing God out of our lives or out of society,

225
00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:21.000
how that can lead to corruption.

226
00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:22.000
So that's there.

227
00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
But actually what's being said in this Psalm seems to be flowing in the opposite direction.

228
00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:32.000
It's because they are corrupt that they do these abominable deeds.

229
00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:35.000
So corrupt actions flow from corrupt hearts.

230
00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:41.000
This is just exactly what Jesus taught in places like Mark chapter 7.

231
00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
So we might look at this.

232
00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
Okay, so there's this pollution that's flowing downstream.

233
00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And so we know that the source of this pollution must be upstream.

234
00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:54.000
You got this evil heart and evil actions are flowing from it.

235
00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:59.000
So is this a special category of person that that applies to?

236
00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.000
Which leads to the third thing we see here.

237
00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:07.000
The fool is not just atheistic and corrupt.

238
00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:10.000
The foolishness spoken of here is universal as well.

239
00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
Universal.

240
00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
So verse two, David gives this mental image of God peering out of heaven

241
00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:18.000
and looking down on humanity.

242
00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:23.000
The Lord looks down from heaven on the children of man to see if there are any who understand,

243
00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
or any who seek after God.

244
00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
It's a bit like the account of the flood in Genesis.

245
00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:36.000
Remember God looks out over mankind and he sees that corruption has affected all of it.

246
00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:42.000
So what does God find this time as he surveys humanity, the children of man?

247
00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:48.000
Well, verse three, once again they have all, notice the word all turned aside,

248
00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:51.000
together they have become corrupt.

249
00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:56.000
There is, note the word, none who does good,

250
00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:01.000
not even one to just drive the point home a bit further.

251
00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:06.000
So the corruption of the human condition is universal.

252
00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:15.000
The way of the fool is the way that we all follow, apart from God's gracious intervention.

253
00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:20.000
So in Psalm 14, you can kind of see a contrast between the world and the people of God

254
00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:25.000
and what's being said, but when you look at the New Testament, how it interprets Psalm 14,

255
00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:30.000
you go to Romans chapter three, Paul quotes Psalm 14 verbatim.

256
00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:33.000
If you feel like I've seen this in the New Testament before, it's because it's there.

257
00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:36.000
Paul quotes this saying, there's none righteous, there's none who does good.

258
00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:43.000
He uses this as, in a way that points to the fact that whether you're Jew or Gentile,

259
00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
all of us have sinned against God.

260
00:19:46.000 --> 00:19:51.000
So put simply, naturally we are all sinners.

261
00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:56.000
And our sin problem isn't just about what we do, it goes deeper than that.

262
00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:00.000
It comes from who we are apart from Christ.

263
00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:08.000
It comes from corrupt hearts that want to be in control rather than welcome God and His reign in our lives.

264
00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:12.000
So without God's gracious intervention, none of us would seek after Him.

265
00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:21.000
We cannot do good unless He graciously cures the corruption that has affected us at the very core.

266
00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:28.000
And if we continue down that path, notice what it says in verse five.

267
00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:34.000
It says, there they are in great terror.

268
00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:38.000
So there's great terror to come for those who continue down the way of the fool.

269
00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
It doesn't end well.

270
00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:46.000
It's a feast like a king, but in the end that will be short-lived, that pleasure.

271
00:20:46.000 --> 00:20:49.000
Because God is with the generation of the righteous.

272
00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
Alright, so that's where we want to be.

273
00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
The way of the fool, the generation of the righteous.

274
00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
It doesn't end well, short-lived for the fool.

275
00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:58.000
So let's see then the generation of the righteous.

276
00:20:58.000 --> 00:21:00.000
So how do we move from that category?

277
00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:04.000
It's not good news at all to the category of the generation of the righteous.

278
00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
Well, as we've already seen in some of the other Psalms,

279
00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
the difference between the righteous person and the unrighteous,

280
00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:12.000
or here the righteous and the fool,

281
00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
is not that one has sinned and the other has it.

282
00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:20.000
So God looks over all of humanity and says, all have sinned.

283
00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:23.000
So the righteous person can't be the person who's gotten it right.

284
00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:28.000
And it can't be the person either who's kind of really kind of turned around

285
00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:33.000
and made themselves better or anything like that.

286
00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:37.000
It's not that they've just changed their ways and started doing right.

287
00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:40.000
Now the difference between the righteous and the unrighteous,

288
00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:42.000
or the righteous and the fool,

289
00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.000
is that the righteous has this right relationship with God.

290
00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:49.000
The difference is found in their relationship to God.

291
00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:53.000
Unlike those who follow the way of the short-sighted fool,

292
00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:57.000
the generation of the righteous will see they welcome the Lord,

293
00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:00.000
they know the Lord's presence dwelling in their life,

294
00:22:00.000 --> 00:22:03.000
and they know the hope that he gives.

295
00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:04.000
So let's see this together.

296
00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:06.000
All right, so the generation of the righteous.

297
00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.000
Unlike the fool, they welcome the Lord.

298
00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
So they call upon the Lord.

299
00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:13.000
We're told in verse 4, at the end,

300
00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:17.000
that the fools do not call upon the name of the Lord.

301
00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:21.000
So the opposite, therefore, must be true about the righteous.

302
00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:24.000
The fool turns aside or away from the Lord,

303
00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.000
but the righteous turn from their sin

304
00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:32.000
and call out to the Lord.

305
00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:34.000
I may have mentioned this before,

306
00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:37.000
but one of my favorite shows in the early 90s was Rescue 911.

307
00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.000
Any of you watch that?

308
00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:40.000
I'm dating myself here.

309
00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:42.000
If you've not seen it,

310
00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.000
people are dating themselves by agreeing with me,

311
00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:46.000
because you've seen this.

312
00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:49.000
If you've not seen it, go on YouTube.

313
00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:53.000
So the basic idea of it is they take actual 911 calls

314
00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.000
and they dramatize them.

315
00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:58.000
There's some really amazing ones that are there.

316
00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.000
And William Shatner is kind of talking you through

317
00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:02.000
what's going on.

318
00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:07.000
But one of my absolute favorites is this teenage boy

319
00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:10.000
who was looking after his younger sibling

320
00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:14.000
and somehow managed to get his tongue stuck in the freezer.

321
00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.000
And so this teenage boy has this predicament.

322
00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
Now, I am stuck in the freezer.

323
00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:21.000
My tongue is stuck there.

324
00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:24.000
I don't want anybody to know about my stupidity here

325
00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:26.000
sticking my tongue in the freezer.

326
00:23:26.000 --> 00:23:28.000
But I need help.

327
00:23:28.000 --> 00:23:30.000
So he's calling out to his sibling for help.

328
00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.000
And eventually the sibling gets the phone to him

329
00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:34.000
and he's got to call out for help.

330
00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
And if you want to hear the best 911 call of all time,

331
00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:39.000
somebody with their tongue stuck in it, it's great.

332
00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:41.000
But here's the point.

333
00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
He had to own up to his stupidity

334
00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:47.000
in order to get the actual help that he needed.

335
00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:49.000
Like you don't get one without the other.

336
00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:52.000
Calling meant owning up.

337
00:23:52.000 --> 00:23:54.000
All right, so this is what we have here.

338
00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:56.000
The righteous are the ones who own up.

339
00:23:56.000 --> 00:23:58.000
They've made the call.

340
00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:02.000
They own up to their sinfulness and call out to God for salvation.

341
00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:05.000
They lay hold of the promise of Scripture.

342
00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:10.000
Whoever shall call upon the name of the Lord shall be saved.

343
00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:12.000
But don't shut him out.

344
00:24:12.000 --> 00:24:14.000
They invite him in.

345
00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:18.000
And this invitation to call upon the Lord is open to everyone.

346
00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:21.000
The call is to come in repentance to the Lord

347
00:24:21.000 --> 00:24:24.000
and to confess him as your Savior and King.

348
00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:28.000
When we do that, he forgives and he saves.

349
00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
This is where our life with him begins.

350
00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:33.000
But it also characterizes our ongoing life with him.

351
00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:37.000
His people are a people of prayer.

352
00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:41.000
So by grace we become those who seek after God

353
00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
to use the language of Psalm 14.

354
00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:45.000
We want to know him more.

355
00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:47.000
We live a life of daily repentance

356
00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:49.000
and trusting in him.

357
00:24:49.000 --> 00:24:54.000
This is the life the Lord wants to give us in Christ.

358
00:24:54.000 --> 00:24:58.000
Hebrews 11 verse 6 describes people of faith in this way.

359
00:24:58.000 --> 00:24:59.000
It says,

360
00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:02.000
He who comes to God must believe that he is

361
00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:06.000
and that he is the rewarder of those who diligently seek him.

362
00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:10.000
People who put their trust in God seek after him in prayer.

363
00:25:10.000 --> 00:25:13.000
But also, so they don't shut God out.

364
00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:15.000
They call him in.

365
00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:19.000
And then they dwell in his presence.

366
00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:20.000
Verse 5 again,

367
00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:22.000
They are in great terror, that's the fools.

368
00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:28.000
For God is with the generation of the righteous.

369
00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:31.000
So when we call upon the Lord, he not only forgives us,

370
00:25:31.000 --> 00:25:37.000
he makes his dwelling within us by his spirit.

371
00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:39.000
And when it says that God is with us,

372
00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.000
it doesn't just convey his presence in our lives.

373
00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:45.000
It also conveys his protection as well.

374
00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:47.000
Throughout the Old Testament, for example,

375
00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:51.000
you see God's people being attacked by foreign armies.

376
00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:55.000
But when the Lord assures them that they're going to be okay,

377
00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:58.000
he assures them by saying, I am with you.

378
00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.000
That's the promise that's put before the Lord's people.

379
00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:02.000
The Lord's presence is with his people.

380
00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:06.000
And that is what is their protection.

381
00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.000
So here in Psalm 14,

382
00:26:08.000 --> 00:26:12.000
the generation of the righteous are opposed and oppressed by the world.

383
00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:14.000
But they have nothing to fear.

384
00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:19.000
Why? Because God is with them.

385
00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
So when Jesus said, go to all the world

386
00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.000
and make disciples of all nations, that's a daunting task.

387
00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:25.000
But then what does he end with? The same promise.

388
00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:29.000
And behold, I am with you always.

389
00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:30.000
Let's see verse 6.

390
00:26:30.000 --> 00:26:32.000
You would shame the plans of the poor,

391
00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:35.000
but the Lord is his refuge.

392
00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:38.000
So the dwelling in the presence of the Lord.

393
00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:39.000
Well, who's the poor here?

394
00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:41.000
Well, the poor, that's the righteous.

395
00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.000
That's the generation of the righteous are described as the poor here.

396
00:26:44.000 --> 00:26:48.000
So the poor are those who are in a place of weakness and vulnerability.

397
00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:52.000
And they are being mocked by the appearance of their weakness and vulnerability.

398
00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:57.000
But they're not bothered because their strength is not found in themselves.

399
00:26:57.000 --> 00:26:59.000
They are not sufficient in and of themselves.

400
00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:01.000
Their sufficiency is of God.

401
00:27:01.000 --> 00:27:03.000
So their strength is found in the Lord.

402
00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:05.000
So they're poor, yes, they're weak, yes.

403
00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:09.000
But they have a strong refuge in the Lord himself.

404
00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:12.000
They know the Lord dwelling with them.

405
00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:13.000
It's like Joseph.

406
00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:19.000
You know, you're reading Genesis, Joseph going through so much years and years of estrangement

407
00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:22.000
and imprisonment and false accusation.

408
00:27:22.000 --> 00:27:24.000
And the list goes on, but it repeatedly says,

409
00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:26.000
but the Lord was with him.

410
00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:27.000
The Lord was with him.

411
00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:30.000
And then because the Lord was with him, the Lord brought him to a place

412
00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:36.000
where things were turned around for the good and for the salvation of many.

413
00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:38.000
Now, this doesn't mean we will not face difficulties,

414
00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:43.000
but it does mean that whatever we face, we can face them knowing that the Lord is with us,

415
00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:51.000
that he is for us, and he will bring us into all the good that he has promised.

416
00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:54.000
The righteous, those who have called upon the Lord can say,

417
00:27:54.000 --> 00:28:00.000
the Lord is with me and he is good and he is powerful.

418
00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:05.000
Lastly, they also hope in his salvation, the generation of the righteous.

419
00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:08.000
So let's read that last verse again.

420
00:28:08.000 --> 00:28:12.000
Oh, that salvation for Israel would come out of Zion.

421
00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:22.000
When the Lord restores the fortunes of his people, let Jacob rejoice, let Israel be glad.

422
00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:27.000
So the psalmist here is living in the hope of the future when everything will be made right,

423
00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:32.000
and all that has been lost will be restored.

424
00:28:32.000 --> 00:28:39.000
So yes, the generation of the righteous is described as poor, as people who are lacking something,

425
00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:42.000
and they're being shamed for their trust in the Lord.

426
00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:48.000
But it ends with saying, we may appear to be poor, but our fortunes are on the way.

427
00:28:48.000 --> 00:28:50.000
They will be restored.

428
00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:55.000
When you get to verse 7, you see that though they may be poor and oppressed now,

429
00:28:55.000 --> 00:29:02.000
the Lord will appear and bring their fortunes with him.

430
00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:06.000
So this kind of restoration of what has been lost comes through Jesus.

431
00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:08.000
All right, so this cry is here.

432
00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:12.000
Oh, that salvation for Israel would come out of Zion.

433
00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:19.000
But from our perspective, looking back on Jesus, we can say, salvation did come out of Zion.

434
00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Jesus did come bringing deliverance from death and sin.

435
00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.000
He brought deliverance and salvation through his own death and resurrection,

436
00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:31.000
through his ascension to his heavenly throne.

437
00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:38.000
And we can rejoice now and we can rejoice in the hope of all that is to come because of Christ

438
00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:40.000
and the blessings that are ours in him.

439
00:29:40.000 --> 00:29:44.000
So if you are in Christ, no matter what is taken from you in the world,

440
00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.000
you have an inheritance in him that nothing can take away.

441
00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:53.000
The fool might want to hold on to everything this life can offer.

442
00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:58.000
If we know Christ, we know that what we have in him is far greater than anything in this world.

443
00:29:58.000 --> 00:30:01.000
Nothing can take that away.

444
00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:05.000
So this is why in Ephesians 2, Paul speaks in this way.

445
00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:09.000
He speaks about God's riches, God being rich in mercy.

446
00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:14.000
Because of the great love with which he loved us, even when we were dead in our trespasses,

447
00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.000
made us alive together with Christ for by grace you have been saved

448
00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:23.000
and raised us up with him and seated us with him in the heavenly places in Christ Jesus.

449
00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:26.000
Why? Why did he do that for us?

450
00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:28.000
So that the fortunes might be restored.

451
00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:30.000
Here's what he says in Ephesians 2, 7.

452
00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:36.000
So that in the coming ages, he might show the immeasurable riches of his grace

453
00:30:36.000 --> 00:30:41.000
in kindness towards us in Christ Jesus.

454
00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:52.000
So yes, fools trade in superior lasting goods for temporary fleeting pleasures of the moment.

455
00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:56.000
We see that just in terms of what we see in the world around us.

456
00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:02.000
I mean, fools like, you know, go for the short term pleasure and leave out the longer term good.

457
00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:07.000
We see that just in this life, but it's also true eternally as well.

458
00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:12.000
The fool says that no God for me in this life.

459
00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:17.000
But they forsake their eternal good in doing that.

460
00:31:17.000 --> 00:31:20.000
There's nothing compared to knowing Christ.

461
00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:25.000
So, yeah, Jim Elliott, the missionary martyr, had it right when he said,

462
00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:32.000
he is no fool who gives what he cannot keep to gain what he cannot lose.

463
00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.000
What we have in Christ is far greater.

464
00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.000
So how shall we respond to this?

465
00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:39.000
Well, heed the warning.

466
00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:43.000
Don't go the way of Nabal.

467
00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:47.000
Our first response looking at this Psalm should be to repent,

468
00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:53.000
to say that is the way that I have gone and I'm turning away from that and I'm turning to Christ.

469
00:31:53.000 --> 00:32:01.000
So unlike Nabal, unlike the fool, welcome Christ as your King.

470
00:32:01.000 --> 00:32:08.000
And he will come and he will forgive and he will make his dwelling in you.

471
00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:11.000
And when he makes his dwelling within us by his spirit,

472
00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:20.000
he helps us to live in the assurance that we have a glorious future that awaits when we will feast with our true King forevermore.

473
00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:30.000
Lord, I pray that you would help us to be a people who heed the warning that we would not be like Nabal.

474
00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:34.000
Lord, that we would not reject our true King.

475
00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:40.000
Lord, I pray that we would welcome Christ into our lives and into every area of our lives.

476
00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:45.000
Lord, as we think about opening up every area of our lives,

477
00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:51.000
Lord, we would admit that there are areas that we struggle where there is sin.

478
00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:56.000
But Lord, we thank you that grace and mercy is abundant in Jesus.

479
00:32:56.000 --> 00:33:01.000
So Lord, I pray that you'd help us to be a people who turn from our sin and repentance.

480
00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:04.000
Welcome Jesus and the forgiveness and cleansing he brings.

481
00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:13.000
Lord, I pray that you'd help us to be a people who gladly know your presence and your help as we look forward to all the good that is to come.

482
00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.000
In Jesus' name, amen.

